        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Ap. 10 1874</date>
                    <salute>My dear Farrer</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am delighted to hear about Coronilla. You must publish an account, &amp; especially with diagrams.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> Pray attend whether the bee penetrates &amp; ruptures with its proboscis the cells on the calyx, as I believe to be the case with the nectaries of Orchis mascula &amp;c.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>I do not quite understand the claw on the vexellum, but I will shew your note to my son Frank.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>yours very sincerely | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">1.2 &amp; ruptures] <hi rend="italic">interl in CD’s hand</hi> </note>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8854.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from T. H. Farrer, [before 10 April 1874]</ref> and n. 2. Farrer published a short paper on fertilisation in <hi rend="italic">Coronilla</hi> (crown vetch) with two diagrams in <hi rend="italic">Nature</hi> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2464.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Farrer 1874</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">In <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6010.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Orchids</hi></ref>, p. 15, CD had described the rupture of the rostellum by bees as they tried to get at the nectary in <hi rend="italic">Orchis mascula</hi> (the early purple orchid).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD refers to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1222.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Francis Darwin</ref>. See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8854.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from T. H. Farrer, [before 10 April 1874]</ref>.</note>
        </div>        
            
